 <h3 class="mt-4 h-notes">Project goal</h3>
 <p>
 To create a tool for searching identical or similar melodies.
 </p>


 <h3 class="mt-4 h-notes">Practical use</h3>
 <p>
 <b>Plagiarism detection</b> — composers produce thousands of new melodies daily. As a result, the risk of accidentally repeating an existing melody increases, while copyright legislation becomes stricter. A melody database, when populated, will allow authors to check their melody for potential matches before publication and thus avoid legal issues.
 </p>
 <p>
 <b>Research</b> — musicologists need accurate tools for comparative analysis of works from different eras, styles, genres, etc. Melody comparison tools will enable, for example, assessing the influence of folk art on a particular composer or the degree of stylistic affinity among a group of authors.
 </p>
 <h3 class="mt-4 h-notes">
 Main functionality:
 </h3>
 <ul>
 <li>Stage1. A database of songs with a collection of MIDI melody files. Ability to add, edit, and delete records.</li>
 <li>Stage2. Melody search by melodic pattern.</li>
 <li>Stage3. Ability to create a MIDI file directly on the site.</li>
 </ul>
